{"cursor":"29207","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\nA 'double bind' is an emotionally distressing dilemma in communication in which\nan individual (or group) receives two or more conflicting messages, in which one\nmessage negates the other. This creates a situation in which a successful\nresponse to one message results in a failed response to the other (and vice\nversa), so that the person will be automatically wrong regardless of response.\nThe double bind occurs when the person cannot confront the inherent dilemma, and\ntherefore cannot resolve it or opt out of the situation.\n\nDouble bind theory was first described by Gregory Bateson and his colleagues in\nthe 1950s. Bateson, G., Jackson, D. D., Haley, J. & Weakland, J. (1956),\nTowards a Theory of Schizophrenia. in Behavioral Science, Vol 1, 251â264\n\nDouble binds are often utilized as a form of control without open coercionâthe\nuse of confusion makes them difficult to respond to or resist. Bateson, G.\n(1972). Double bind, 1969. Steps to an ecology of the mind: A revolutionary\napproach to man's understanding of himself, 271-278. Chicago: University of\nChicago Press\n\nA double bind generally includes different levels of abstraction in orders of\nmessages, and these messages can be stated or implicit within the context of the\nsituation, or conveyed by tone of voice or body language. Further complications\narise when frequent double binds are part of an ongoing relationship to which\nthe person or group is committed. Bateson, G., Jackson,\nD. D., Haley, J. & Weakland, J., 1956, Toward a theory of schizophrenia. (in:\n'Behavioral Science', vol.1, 251â264) {{cite book\n | author=Bateson, Gregory title=Steps to an Ecology of Mind: Collected Essays\n | in Anthropology, Psychiatry, Evolution, and Epistemology publisher=University\n | Of Chicago Press | year=1972}}\n\nDouble bind theory is more clearly understood in the context of complex systems\nand cybernetics, because human communication and also the mind itself function\nin an interactive manner similar to ecosystems. Complex systems theory helps us\nunderstand the interdependence of the parts of a message and provides \"an\nordering of what to the Newtonian looks like chaos.\"\n","linknr":430,"url":"Double_bind","recorded":1364056932,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Double_bind&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Double_bind&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Political_anthropology","/wiki/Medical_anthropology","/wiki/Psychological_anthropology","/wiki/Cognitive_anthropology","/wiki/Culture-bound_syndrome","/wiki/Help:Template","/wiki/Template:Sidebar_subsection","/wiki/Wikipedia:Templates_for_discussion/Log/2013_March_20#Template:Sidebar_subsection","/wiki/Help:Template","/wiki/Template:Sidebar_subsection","/wiki/Wikipedia:Templates_for_discussion/Log/2013_March_20#Template:Sidebar_subsection","/wiki/Ethnomedicine","/wiki/Clinical_Ethnography","/wiki/Critical_medical_anthropology","/wiki/Cross-cultural_psychiatry","/wiki/Person-centered_ethnography","/wiki/Society_for_Medical_Anthropology","/wiki/Syndemic","/wiki/Gregory_Bateson","/wiki/Maurice_Bloch","/wiki/Charles_L._Briggs","/wiki/Veena_Das","/wiki/Geor